1 adults; and
2 WHEREAS, schools, colleges, universities, healthcare providers, and community
3 organizations may play an important role in supporting prevention, awareness, and early
4 intervention efforts; and
5 WHEREAS, modern public health approaches increasingly utilize digital education
6 tools, voluntary self-assessment resources, and mobile support services to improve
7 accessibility and engagement; and
8 WHEREAS, Louisiana has the opportunity to evaluate innovative and
9 evidence-informed approaches to problem gambling prevention and support that may
10 improve access to information, education, and behavioral health resources across the state.
11 THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED that the Senate of the Legislature of Louisiana
12 does hereby urge and request the Louisiana Department of Health to study opportunities to
13 modernize Louisiana's problem gambling prevention and education efforts, with a particular
14 focus on youth, college-age populations, and young adults.
15 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the department is urged to examine opportunities
16 for age-appropriate educational resources and curriculum addressing gambling-related
17 harms, financial literacy, decision-making, online gaming environments, and responsible
18 behavior.
19 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the department is urged to examine the use of
20 voluntary digital tools and mobile resources designed to support prevention, self-assessment,
21 awareness, early intervention, and connection to behavioral health and recovery support
22 services.
23 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the department is urged to consult with the
24 Louisiana Department of Education, the Louisiana Board of Regents, colleges and
25 universities, behavioral health providers, community organizations, researchers, and other
26 relevant stakeholders in developing its findings and recommendations.
27 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the department is urged to submit a written
28 report of its findings and recommendations to the Senate and the David R. Poynter
29 Legislative Research Library, as required by R.S. 24:771 and 772, no later than February 1,
30 2027.
